snippet.textDisplay:
Chris I’m shaking my head on this one! Shop vac/wet dry, pump up sprayer full of carpet shampoo and a drill brush. Vac, spray, agitate, extract and rinse, extract again! Wet dry vac works great for extracting carpets. For the dirty plastic bits use the drill brush again with a good cleaner. Wipe away with a microfiber towel. Follow up with favorite plastic dressing, No need to use paper towels! The method you used is going to leave a film of soap that will attract more dirt.
Paint correction/ polish job looked great! Just gotta bump up the interior cleaning!

snippet.textDisplay:
Couple things (disclaimer at the end): A professional-level random orbital polisher like the Porter Cabel or a Griots Garage polisher is only $115-150 plus another $20 or so in professional foam pads from Chemical Guys or generic on amazon for less.  There's a super-strong aversion to the use of "specialty" and power tools on this channel because Chris wants his projects to be approachable to the every-man, and I respect that. And its nice that he has the work ethic to do this by hand but its the equivalent to cutting 2/4s for a framing project with a handsaw when a circular saw is really the right tool for the job and can be bought pretty inexpensively. Compare $150 DA polisher that is safe on paint even if youre not skilled (vs a rotary polisher that can burn paint) and will save you probably 8-10 hours or more of polishing to the $89 toque wrench Chris recommends and has affiliate links to, or the $475 impact driver he has a link to in his suspension video.  Using the RIGHT tool for the job is just as important as anything else.  The polisher will be worth its weight in gold if you plan to do this.  Ive polished cars by hand, and I DO NOT recommend it at all.

Also the ultimate line of Meguairs products have tons of oil in them. Not saying results look bad, or that some of that oxidation wasn't removed but a lot of that depth coming back will be from the oils soaking into the porosity of the oxidation. Plus the fact that Chris went straight from polish to wax without stripping the oils makes me wonder how much the oils are just masking fade compared to how much oxidation actually got cut through. Its obviously better than when he started but if you look at 10:20 after he used alcohol to prep for touchup paint, it looks almost like the alcohol removed the oils and the paint is still oxidized underneath.  These oils will come off after a couple of washes, and the wax apllied on top will not adhere to the paint as well without prepping the paint (like a full alcohol wipe, Car Pro Eraser, or Gyeon Prep) before applying wax/sealant.  

Chris I love your channel, and I hate being critical of your videos because I know you put considerable time, effort and passion into them.  This chevy was revived by your work, especially considering the price you paid for it.  So dont take this comment as a negative, but maybe some alternative viewpoints, additional info, and things for all of us to consider when we work on our cars and our customer's paint.
